{"id":1351,"date":"2011-02-18T06:25:46","date_gmt":"2011-02-18T12:25:46","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/like_fish_out_of_water.php"},"modified":"2011-02-18T06:25:46","modified_gmt":"2011-02-18T12:25:46","slug":"like_fish_out_of_water","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/like_fish_out_of_water.php","title":{"rendered":"Like Fish out of Water"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/ljs_logo.gif\" alt=\"Long John Silver's Logo, Before and After\" \/><\/p>\n<p>First opened in 1969 in Louisville, KY, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ljsilvers.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Long John Silver&#8217;s<\/a> (LJS) is a QSR (Quick Service Restaurant) seafood chain with over 1,100 locations worldwide, but mostly in the U.S. Privately owned until 1998, LJS is currently part of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.yum.com\/company\/ourbrands.asp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Yum! Brands<\/a>, who also own KFC, Taco Bell, and Pizza Hut. I&#8217;ve never been into a LJS but I&#8217;m guessing they are no different in expectations and delivery from what its sister brands offer. Leading up to Lent season this March &mdash; where fish consumption increases as meat is verboten &mdash; <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ljsilvers.com\/misc\/press\/021011.asp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">LJS is unveiling<\/a> a new identity and tagline, &#8220;We Speak Fish.&#8221;<\/p><!--more--><p><img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/ljs_logo_detail.jpg\" alt=\"Long John Silver's Logo, Detail\" \/><\/p>\n<iframe title=\"YouTube video player\" width=\"574\" height=\"353\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/TWbmMFgbvWc?rel=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen><\/iframe>\n<br \/><br \/>\n<p class=\"caption\">15-second spot introducing the new logo and tagline.<\/p>\n<iframe title=\"YouTube video player\" width=\"560\" height=\"349\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/bFedciZfn78?rel=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen><\/iframe>\n<br \/><br \/>\n<p class=\"caption\">Long John Silver&#8217;s Chief Marketing Officer talks about the new look.<\/p>\n<p>The new look attempts to change the perception of LJS from a low-end, boppy fast-food chain to a faux, semi-upscale one. A worthy goal, but a really hard one to achieve, especially when a lot of their locations are still housed in what look like smelly fisherman cottages.\n<p><img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/ljs_old_store.jpg\" alt=\"Long John Silver's Logo, Detail\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"caption\">Older restaurants. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.flickr.com\/photos\/wafflewhiffer\/2795454628\/sizes\/z\/in\/photostream\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Image source<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/ljs_new_store.jpg\" alt=\"Long John Silver's Logo, Detail\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"caption\">Newer restaurants, paired with sister brand, KFC, both owned by Yum! Brands. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.flickr.com\/photos\/mortonfox\/42919358\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Image source<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s assume we are willing to take that leap. The typography is indeed nice and upscale-ish in the slender, tracked out sans serif (Trade Gothic?) but the fish icon bring its down again to that cheap fast-food look with all those swirlies. It&#8217;s not bad-bad, just okay-bad. The best thing about the whole upgrade is the tagline, not that it&#8217;s groundbreaking, but it&#8217;s cute and it helps LJS sound like an accessible place that doesn&#8217;t have the typical cheeseburger offerings of most fast-food chains.<\/p>\n<p class=\"bottom\">Thanks to James I. Bowie for the tip.<\/p>","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<script type=\"text\/javascript\" src=\"swfobject.js\"><\/script>\n<scri